===========================================================================
SUMMARY: WHAT THE HARD SCIENCES OFFER
===========================================================================

| Category          | Precision  | New free params? | Testable? |
|-------------------|------------|------------------|-----------|
| Turbulence        | 2-3 digits | No (emergent)    | NO        |
| Molecular spectra | 6-8 digits | No (from α)      | Redundant |
| Crystallography   | 5-8 digits | No (from α, Z)   | Redundant |
| Math constants    | arbitrary  | N/A (not physics) | YES *     |
| Cosmology         | 2-4 digits | YES (6 params)   | Marginal  |
| Nuclear physics   | 7-11 digits| Partially (m_q)  | YES       |

* Feigenbaum constants: PSLQ null against our basis

THREE GENUINELY NEW THINGS TO TEST:

  1. m_p/m_e = 1836.153 (11 digits, PSLQ null at maxcoeff 10000)
     This is the most precise mass ratio in physics.
     It depends on QCD (proton mass) and QED (electron mass).
     It's NOT a simple function of transcendentals.

  2. Cosmological parameters (Ω_b, Ω_c, n_s, H₀, T₀)
     These ARE free parameters, different from SM's 18.
     Precision is marginal (2-4 digits) but improving.
     The CMB temperature T₀ = 2.72548 K is the most precise.

  3. Nuclear binding energies (deuteron: 2.224566 MeV)
     These depend on quark masses and α_s through QCD.
     They're derived quantities but the derivation is
     from lattice QCD — a different path than perturbative QED.

BOTTOM LINE:
  The hard sciences outside physics offer mostly DERIVED quantities
  (from α and nuclear charges) at insufficient precision.
  The exceptions are cosmological parameters (new free params,
  low precision) and nuclear masses (high precision, but
  derived from QCD which we already tested through α_s).

  The von Kármán constant and other turbulence parameters
  are intriguing UNKNOWNS but at 2-3 digit precision,
  PSLQ and modular search cannot operate.
  